  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">8 Water Well Rehabilitations in Apac District, Uganda</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In additional to rehabilitating eight boreholes, activities to promote the community ownership and maintenance of these water points included:
1) training 73 Water User Committee (WUC) members in borehole oversight and
maintenance (O&amp;amp;M) procedures, including the collection of water user fees;
2) training 8 caretakers to track borehole functionality and report breakdowns;
3) training each WUC in the steps to open a bank account to promote the safe and transparent storage of water point maintenance funds; and
4) training 561 community members in the best practices in hygiene and sanitation through a two-day workshop.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In partnership with Generosity.org, International Lifeline Fund improved access to clean water in eight villages across the Apac District of Northern Uganda by rehabilitating eight dysfunctional boreholes. In addition to hardware repairs, Lifeline has built upon measures to support a pre-existing clean water ecosystem to minimize the risks of borehole malfunctions while maximizing the prospects that timely corrective action will be taken when water access problems do arise. In doing so, Lifeline and Generosity.org have benefitted a total of 4,965 household beneficiaries.</narrative>
  </description>
